-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-12-21/bhp-energy-resources-lend-lease-lynas-woodside-australia-n-z-stocks.html
Australia’s  S&P/ASX 200 Index  rose
0.1 percent to 4,778.40 at the 4:10 p.m. close of trading in
Sydney. New Zealand’s  NZX 50 Index  added 0.1 percent to 3,322.38
at the 5 p.m. close in Wellington.  The following were among the most active shares in the
market today. Stock symbols are in parentheses after company
names.  Mining shares: Copper for delivery in three months jumped
1.8 percent on the London Metal Exchange yesterday, after
touching an all-time high.  BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining
company, gained 0.9 percent to A$45.82.  Rio Tinto Group  (RIO AU),
the world’s third-biggest miner, rose 0.1 percent to A$86.78.  Centro Properties Group  (CNP AU) gained 3.3 percent to 15.5
Australian cents. The Australian shopping-mall owner that ceded
control to creditors in 2008 said it has received several
expressions of interest in its Australian and U.S. assets.       Energy Resources of Australia Ltd.  (ERA AU) slumped 5.5
percent to A$11.29. The uranium producer controlled by Rio Tinto
Group was downgraded to “underperform” from “sector perform”
at RBC Capital Markets. The shares plunged 9.3 percent yesterday
after the company forecast a drop of as much as 83 percent in
profit for the year.       Lend Lease Group  (LLC AU) dropped 1.1 percent to A$8.65.
Australia’s largest developer was downgraded to “hold” from
“buy” at Deutsche Bank AG, according to Bloomberg data.       Lynas Corp.  (LYC AU), a miner of rare earths, gained 4.4
percent to A$1.66. The company said it got approval from the
Malawi government to complete the acquisition of a rare earths
resource.  To contact the reporter on this story:
